	<section id="comments-area">
					<section id="promoted-comments">
				<h2 class="subheading"><span class="full">Promoted Comments</span></h2>
				<ul>
						<li class="comment" data-post-score="4" data-post-negative="0" data-post-positive="4" data-post-id="25688501" data-poster-id="6560">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="Smeghead"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=6560">Smeghead</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Praefectus</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
          
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/business/2013/11/new-fcc-chairman-tells-wireless-carriers-to-unlock-cell-phones/?comments=1&amp;post=25688501#comment-25688501" class="timeago datetime">jump to post</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
        
        
            
          
        
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      Not a bad start. We'll see if he keeps this up.<br><br>My own experience with unlocking has only been with AT&amp;T, and has been quite mixed. When we wanted to have our dumbphones unlocked for a trip home, they were reasonable about it. We were out of contract already, and they provided unlock codes with little prodding.<br><br>Last year's encounter didn't go so smoothly. I had to jump on a plane to Scotland with about a day's notice when my Dad was gravely ill. One of the things I wanted to do was unlock my iPhone 4 so I could pop a SIM card into it when I got there. AT&amp;T couldn't have made the process more difficult if they'd tried.<br><br>I was less than 10 bloody days away from the end of my contract, and they were right shits about it. It took about an hour of arguing for them to relent, and they stalled long enough in setting up the unlock that I ran out of time to do the unlock dance with itunes before leaving. I ended up carrying my old dumbphone for the duration of the trip along with my iphone, which I used wherever I could find wifi. Bastards.<br><br>Instead of proposing that unlocks be allowed, how about pushing for subsidy locks to be made illegal instead? There's no need for them; if you've received a subsidy on a phone, you've already signed a contract by which you're legally bound until its expiration, so there's zero need for the phones to be locked in the first place.<br><br>Subsidy locking is a sham, and always has been.
      
    </div>
